title: For Sale/Trade:  Pre-war Walther PPK
postcontent:
I have a Walther PPK in .32 ACP that was made in 1935-1936, serial is 8761XX. The outside has some finish wear and light pitting, likely from being used/carried during WW2. The interior is in excellent shape, and the bore looks perfect. It's in excellent mechanical condition, with little wear to the internals. It comes with a wartime magazine, and a holster. The holster is unmarked, it has some damage to the magazine holder, but is in great shape otherwise and is likely original to the pistol.

The interesting thing is the slide is engraved, it says "Deutsche Jägerschaft Jagdkreis Aichach" Which means German Hunter's association, Hunting district Aichach. It was an organization that controlled hunting in Germany, and the pistol probably belonged to a member.

I picked this up in a trade recently, but it doesn't really fit my collection, and I could use a carry gun more than it so I am mostly looking to trade this. I am looking for something more suitable to carry, I'd really like a commander length 1911, or a P229 in .40, but I would consider other trades.

I have more pictures that I can email.

Harry Reid shoots down Feinstein gun-ban bill

**FILE** Sen. Dianne Feinstein seeks to reimpose weapons bans that expired in 2004. The California Democrat’s current bill would go further than her 1994 law, which was sunsetted. (Associated Press)
By Cheryl K. Chumley -The Washington Times Tuesday, March 19, 2013
Sen. Dianne Feinstein emerged from a closed-door meeting with Majority Leader Harry Reid on Monday — but her ban on assault weapons and high-capacity ammunition magazines didn’t.

Mr. Reid turned down her attempt to bring her ban on 157 different weapons and ammunition clips aboard the Democratic Party’s comprehensive gun bill, Politico reported.

“My understanding is it will not be [part of the base bill],” said Mrs. Feinstein, California Democrat. “I would like to [see it moved], but the leader has decided not to do it. … You will have to ask him [why].”

Her bill instead will have to go forth separately or as an amendment — and that means it’s probably not going anywhere.

Conservative blog Hot Air characterizes its chances for passage by itself as near zero and counts supporters at about 35.

Mr. Reid’s decision was likely aimed at bolstering the party’s chances to pass some gun control, even if it’s not as restrictive as many on the left would like. As Hot Air noted, Mr. Reid can now play the two bills off each other and make the case that he kept out Mrs. Feinstein’s more controversial version.

Mr. Reid is also likely looking at the 2014 elections, when several Democratic Senate seats are open for contest in conservative states, analysts say.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Why buy the AK Parts Kits when you can get the complete rifle for less!
postcontent:
I have noticed lately that the AK's and AK part Kits that have been posted on ARMSLIST are going for outrages prices. 500, 600 and up, I mean way up.  You can buy a complete AK 47 rifle from classic arms for 799.00 and that comes with 4 30 round magazines and a tactical carrying case, and oh ya they're in stock.  The magazines alone a worth 120 dollars or more, plus the tactical carrying case is probably 50 bucks.  That means the gun sells for around 600+/-, and it is built and ready for the range.  For those that haven't built an AK47 from a parts kit......it is fun, but far more expensive than you would think.  You will need to buy numerous amounts of tools and dies to complete your build.  There are some shops out there that will build your AK's for you but it will cost, typically upwards of a hundred dollars. Ak's are going to come back down in prices just wait and be patient.  When the part kits comeback down where it makes it cost effective go ahead and build.  Oh ya don't forget your 922r compliance costs when you build.

Oh ya here is the link to classic arms:
http://www.classicfirearms.com/long-guns/1975gpak

Respectfully Yours,
Toe Cutter

title: For Sale:  Colt series 70 1911 is a SCAM
location: He lives in High Springs, Gainesville, Florida
postcontent:
This is a response to this ad placed earlier today:
http://www.armslist.com/posts/1292185/gainesville-florida-handguns-for-sale--colt-45-acp-marrk-iv-70-series-government-model-stainless-steel

FOR THE SAKE OF CLARITY, I HAVE COPIED THE ORIGINAL POST AS FOLLOWS:
"As title says .. colt mark iv 70 series stainless steel 1911
Good condition have 3 magazines. They hold 14. Rounds
Also can include ammo depending on offer. Will to trade plus cash or just
Trade. Or just sell .. make a offer. And please dont waste either of are time with a ridiculous
Offer this is a high quality gun and high capacity .. not many around for sale.
Any questions or offers text 352-278-4929 ."

For those of you who may not be familiar with the 1911 pistols, this is a warning that this ad is for a "Frankenstein" 1911. Colt NEVER has made a high capacity 1911 pistol. The only part of this gun that is of Colt production is the slide, and because of it being a series 70, we can guess it came from a Colt manufactured prior to 1983 when its production line was cancelled. 
The frame and parts of this gun that you can see in the picture are not of colt manufacture, but instead this "high quality and rare" gun is a home-built collaboration of cheap and mismatched parts. The rear sight is not even for a 1911 pistol, and hangs out over the back of the slide. The front sight is what appears to be a "glue on" home job of some type or another. The beavertail safety does not match the frame, and considering how low it is sitting in the frame, is probably disabled or does not work at all. You can see by examining the pictures that the seller has "rubbed out" the marking on the barrel so you cannot see its stamping, and the manufacturers label on the frame has been edited so it cannot be read as well. I am guessing that it may be an older Caspian high capacity frame, but it is more likely a frame that was bought unfinished such as this one:
http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=333040302. or possibly an el-cheapo STI or RIA frame from the Philippines. 

I would steer clear of this obvious scam, but if you are desperate, please do not pay more than a couple hundred bucks for the sum of its hashed-together parts, as it is quite likely that most have been damaged beyond use. Better yet, report obvious scammer's like this one and get it removed before an un-knowledgeable buyer gets ripped off.

title: For Sale:  Let's get this all back to normal
postcontent:
Feinstein: Reid excluded the assault-weapons ban from Senate gun bill
Feinstein: Reid excluded the assault-weapons ban from Senate gun bill
POSTED AT 9:21 AM ON MARCH 19, 2013 BY ED MORRISSEY


No one expected the assault-weapons ban proposed by Dianne Feinstein to pass as part of the Senate’s gun-control package. Now it won’t even be a part of it. Last night, Feinstein told reporters that Harry Reid had excluded it from the final version of the legislative package:

Sen. Dianne Feinstein (D-Calif.) said on Monday that a controversial assault weapons ban will not be part of a Democratic gun bill that was expected to reach the Senate floor next month.

After a meeting with Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid (D-Nev.) on Monday, a frustrated Feinstein said she learned that the bill she sponsored — which bans 157 different models of assault weapons and high-capacity ammunition magazines — wouldn’t be part of a Democratic gun bill to be offered on the Senate floor. Instead, it can be offered as an amendment. But its exclusion from the package makes what was already an uphill battle an almost certain defeat.
“Almost certain defeat”? Left on its own as an amendment, Feinstein’s bill would be lucky to get 35 votes. She knows it, too, which is why she vented her frustration:

“My understanding is it will not be [part of the base bill],” Feinstein said. “It will be separate.”

Asked if she were concerned about the decision, Feinstein paused and said, “Sure. I would like to [see the bill moved], but the leader has decided not to do it.”

“You will have to ask him [Reid],” she said, when asked why the decision was made.
Do we need to ask? Reid can be accused of many things, but he’s not clueless when it comes to the politics of guns. Reid wants to pass a bipartisan bill to expand background checks, and he’s more than willing to sacrifice Feinstein’s effort to get it, especially since Reid was never enthusiastic about the renewed AWB in the first place.

This way, he gets two wins. First, using Feinstein’s proposal as the extreme of the effort, the background-check legislation looks more reasonable, even where it may not be. Second, by allowing Democrats in red states to vote against the AWB in a separate floor action, he protects them from attacks in the 2014 election. It’s a win-win for Reid.

It’s more of a mixed bag for gun-rights advocates. Depending on whether the Senate bill includes federal registration of all firearms, it’s a big loss — but that has absolutely no chance of passing the House anyway, and Republicans in the Senate won’t have any reason to stick around if it does. If it doesn’t, it’s more of a headache than a problem. The upside will be the outright rejection of the AWB, which should stick a stake through its heart for another decade after politicians who took the risk to demand it ended up with egg on their faces.

title: For Sale:  Senate Democrats Cave And Drop Assault Weapons Ban From Major Gun Legislation
postcontent:
From the Associated Press 3-19-13
California Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein announced Tuesday that a new assault weapons will not be included as part of a forthcoming comprehensive gun control bill, according to the Associated Press. 

While this doesn't mean that the ban – which would make it illegal to purchase a set of firearms deemed by regulators as "assault weapons"  — is off the table permanently, the measure won't be included in a major reform package that is expected to reach the Senate floor next month. 

Possibly contributing to the removal of the ban is the political liability the bill would pose for a number of Senate Democrats in the 2014 midterm elections. Some Democrats have also expressed reluctance that including the assault weapons ban would doom the rest of the comprehensive package. 
 It's unlikely that a ban on assault weapons would have any chance of passage in the GOP-controlled House of Representatives, potentially causing a "poison pill" for comprehensive gun control reform.
 Three other gun control measure were approved by the Senate Judiciary Committee this month, including an expansion of federal background checks for gun buyers, increased penalties for gun trafficking, and an increase to school safety money.

title: For Sale:  AR15 in 300 Blackout, 303 Enfiled Sporter, H&K 416-22 for sale
postcontent:
Three rifles for sale today, the price of ammo and difficulties getting lanes at ranges makes shooting them less enjoyable and more difficult for me. Plus there are a few project cars and my upcoming wedding I could use the money for. So, these are up for sale as a result. The following three rifles are for sale:

Custom 300 Blackout AR-15 Build
Aero Keyhole A3 upper
Kreiger Stainless Match Barrel, .750 profiled, carbine gas ported with a standard A2 FH
PSA Multi-marked lower (no specific cal marking, picto, good to gofor hunting in other states)
DPMS LPK with enhanced roll pins, pins are roughly twice as thick as standard lpk equipment
BCM MPI/MPC BCG and Bolt, staked, peened, and nearly brand new
Milspec buffer tube, spring, and buffer
Hogue grip
Magpul enhanced trigger guard 
Magpul CTR stock
DPMS Freefloat tube and nut
Will come with various mags (USGI, Magpul 20 &30, Lancer 20)
Excellent rifle, extremely accurate, heavy hitting and fun to shoot. To build another you'd be looking at waiting for barrels, bcg's, ect... I've shot less than 500 rounds through it, basically testing different factory loads and hand loads to find what's best. I built it for a hog hunt that appears likely won't be happening now. It'll come with a scope and rings that are sitting on top of it and are sited in with 147gr super loads. Looking to get $2,000 obo for it, I had a few offers higher than this before, but wasn't REALLY looking to sell at the time. 

Next up is a British Enfield SMLE (1916) in 303 British that's been partially sporterized. All matching numbers, head spacing is great, all functions as it should, no issues to note at all. Wood is in great shape, rifling is good, bluing is still pretty strong and there aren't any visual defects to note at all. It has the forend wood cut down and no longer has the top wood covering the barrel. Also has a different front sight and leather sling. Great looking rifle, just haven't been able to shoot it like I would like. Looking for $400 obo

Last up is the one that'll get me in trouble if it sells, the HK 416-22 rifle. It has a Barksa holographic red dot on top, foregrip, utg rail covers, and is simply a blast to shoot. I've put a LOT of ammo through it, and the rifling shows no signs of giving up at all, and has had one malfunction ever which was due to lack of cleaning in a test of the rifle. Functions perfectly, and is a blast to shoot. Fiance said not to sell it, so the price reflects her desire to keep it around the house. $600 firm on it, because I could buy her something shinny if it sold.
